{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}
{{Use British English|date=January 2018}}
[[File:Pioneer Helmet.jpg|thumb|alt=Colour photograph of the Pioneer Helmet|The 100–200 fragments of the [[Pioneer Helmet|Pioneer helmet]] were adhered using HMG.]]
'''HMG Heat and Waterproof Adhesive''' (also known as '''HMG''' or '''HMG adhesive''') is a brand of [[Nitrocellulose|cellulose nitrate]] adhesive manufactured by H Marcel Guest Ltd. It is one of the most popular cellulose nitrate adhesives used in [[Conservation-restoration of cultural heritage|conservation and restoration]] work, and is used on materials such as metal, wood, glass, and pottery.{{sfn|Shashoua|Bradley|Daniels|1992|p=114}}{{sfn|HMG product page}}{{sfn|MFA CAMEO|2016}} It is sometimes referred to as "the blue tube", in contrast to "the purple tube", the acrylic B72 Restoration Adhesive also manufactured by the company.{{sfn|HMG Adhesives|2011}}

HMG was invented during [[World War II]] by the company's founder, Herbert Falder.{{sfn|HMG Adhesives|2011}} Today it is broadly used, including by the [[British Museum]] and the [[York Archaeological Trust]]. In 1997, HMG was used to adhere pieces of the [[Anglo-Saxons|Anglo-Saxon]] [[Pioneer Helmet|Pioneer helmet]], which was found broken into between 100 and 200 fragments.{{sfn|Meadows|2004|pp=24–27}}{{sfn|Read|2006|pp=39–42}} Particularly fragile areas had their cracks injected with a solution of HMG diluted 50% with [[acetone]], to consolidate them and prevent them from collapsing; holes made while cleaning away corrosion were likewise injected with pigmented HMG.{{sfn|Meadows|2004|pp=25–26}}{{sfn|Read|2006|p=40}} Stronger areas, such as the [[Dexter and sinister|sinister]] cheek guard, found in eighteen pieces, and the [[nasal helmet|nasal]], were joined directly with the adhesive.{{sfn|Meadows|2004|pp=24–25}} Finally, HMG was also used to adhere glass fibre matting on the inside of the helmet, strengthening weak joins and covering gaps, the latter to provide backing against which gapfill could be applied.{{sfn|Meadows|2004|pp=27}}{{sfn|Read|2006|p=42}}

==Technical properties==
HMG is advertised with a {{convert|-18|C|F|abbr=on}} [[flash point]], and a {{convert|100|C|F|abbr=on}} temperature resistance.{{sfn|HMG product page}} It is insoluble in water and soluble in acetone, and is composed of 70% amyl acetate solvent, 25% cellulose nitrate, approximately 5% of the plasticizer dibutyl phthalate,{{sfn|Shashoua|Bradley|Daniels|1992|p=115}} and a small amount of a phenolic resin leveling agent.{{sfn|MFA CAMEO|2016}} The adhesive is touch dry in five minutes, and hard dry in ten.{{sfn|HMG Adhesives|2011}}

